{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621810"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16776"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16776"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.91,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9467"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53339"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"524"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5129"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22727"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman purchases over-the-counter calcium carbonate tablets for intermittent heartburn symptoms. She experiences relief within minutes of taking the medication.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of this agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibition of gastric acid secretion","Stimulation of mucus production","Direct neutralisation of stomach acid","Reduction of lower oesophageal sphincter tone","Enhancement of gastric emptying"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect neutralisation of stomach acid\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of antacids, such as calcium carbonate tablets. These medications contain basic compounds that react chemically with hydrochloric acid in the stomach to form water and neutral salt products.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of gastric acid secretion\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of proton pump inhibitors and histamine receptor antagonists, not antacids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile some antacids may have mild protective effects, \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulation of mucus production\u003C/strong\u003E is not their primary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduction of lower oesophageal sphincter tone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as antacids do not significantly affect sphincter tone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntacids do not primarily affect gastric motility and do not \u003Cstrong\u003Eenhance gastric emptying.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon antacid compounds include calcium carbonate, magnesium hydroxide, and aluminium hydroxide. The neutralisation reaction provides rapid but temporary relief from acid-related symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antacids work by directly neutralising stomach acid through chemical reactions with hydrochloric acid.","Common antacid compounds include calcium carbonate, magnesium hydroxide, and aluminium hydroxide.","Antacids provide rapid but short-term relief from acid-related symptoms."],"references":["